tr.th: Conclusion and Recommendations based on this report and previous findings known to us

tr.td: The patient shows markedly elevated creatinine, proteinuria, glucosuria, ketonuria, and bilirubinuria, with low urine specific gravity and abnormal urine appearance, suggesting significant renal dysfunction, possibly acute or chronic kidney disease with impaired filtration. Blood glucose and HbA1c are not elevated, making diabetes less likely. Elevated chloride may indicate metabolic acidosis. Urine findings (cloudy, brown, ammoniacal) may suggest underlying renal or hepatic pathology. Prompt nephrology evaluation is recommended.
